{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"964556fc-355e-495c-9df5-dfdc29b7e8c5","content":"The directory is empty, so I'll answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI APIs.\n\n**Both properties you found are outdated/incorrect for .NET 10.**\n\n### `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`\nThis was a **Xamarin.Forms** API (`Xamarin.Forms.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific`). In .NET MAUI, the equivalent is handled differently — **MAUI respects safe areas by default** on iOS. Content is automatically laid out within the safe area without needing this property.\n\n### `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`\nThis is **not a valid property** in .NET MAUI. It doesn't exist on `Grid` or other layouts.\n\n### What to do in .NET MAUI (.NET 10):\n\n- **Safe area is respected by default** — no opt-in needed.\n- To make a background image extend **behind** the notch/status bar, use padding adjustments or set the element to fill the entire page and layer content on top with proper margins.\n- You can also use `On<iOS>().SetUseSafeArea(false)` in code-behind if you need to **opt out** of safe area insets on a page, then manually handle padding.\n\n```xml\n<!-- Typical pattern: full-bleed background + safe content -->\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\" ...>\n    <Grid>\n        <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        <StackLayout Padding=\"{OnPlatform iOS='0,47,0,34'}\" ...>\n            <!-- your content here -->\n        </StackLayout>\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe tutorial you found is likely written for Xamarin.Forms, not .NET MAUI.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"97ec74f6-7351-4c26-a61d-f064aa15cc11","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"A853:77FDA:73C390:85A280:69FBE640"},"id":"3dbab68e-2ff9-4e30-900e-c9d6b8e7d793","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:09:31.994Z","parentId":"49d8481e-59d1-419f-9f90-dfe604e0abd2"}
